      {
        "id": 2330192,
        "name": "John Morris",
        "username": "John_Morris",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/john_morris/{size}/840_2.png",
        "created_at": "2018-01-05T18:00:24.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Drunk with Patricia Wells\u2019s Provencal daube (beef stew with mushrooms and orange zest), a very versatile dish for reds.</p>\n<p><strong>2015 J. Drouhin - Cote de Beaune - Village (rouge):</strong> This was a surprise from the outset \u2013 riper, richer and darker-fruited than I expected. The vintage speaking, I guess. Ripe bing cherry flavors, with an overlay of plum (vs. the more red cherry profile or maybe strawberry I\u2019d expect). Much riper and fruitier than I\u2019d have expected from a lesser appellation from Drouhin. This was tasty from the moment it was poured \u2013 no decanting, and without food. In the mouth, this had that same ripe bing cherry flavor and perhaps a bit of dark plum. No sign of oak (it sees 10% new oak). There\u2019s ample acid and tannin to give it structure, but it\u2019s open for business. In texture \u2013 the feel of the fruit and tannin and acid \u2013 it reminded me of some cool climate New World pinot, but without any candy/cough drop flavors (thank goodness). Really a pleasure. It scratches the pinot itch and is a steal at around $25 \u2013 <em>an absolute steal.</em> 89-ish.</p>\n<p><strong>2005 Edmunds St. John - Parmalee-Hill Vineyard (Sonoma Valley) - Syrah):</strong> Decanted three hours ahead, which yielded a bit of reduction at first. Like a bottle three years ago, this was a little simple and four-square. Lots of plummy fruit, ample softening tannins and acid, but not a lot of secondary development. Softer and riper than I usually expect Steve\u2019s wines to be. (The '05 Bassetti this summer was even softer and riper.)<br>\nI couldn\u2019t tell if this is all there is. At points, I felt this wine was like a fortress and that it was guarding its treasures. Not sure what to say. I think I have at least one more bottle. I\u2019ll wait three to five years before trying that to see if it evolves more. At the moment, 85-ish \u2013 pleasant enough but not that interesting. One day? Who knows.</p>",
